\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 I.\tab It Is Likely That Capital Boost Did Not Violate Title VII Because It Offered a Facial Accommodation Barat Rejected and Faced Significant Operational Burdens That Support an Undue Hardship Defense.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, employers must reasonably accommodate an employee\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s sincerely held religious beliefs or practices unless doing so would impose an \u8220\'93undue hardship on the conduct of the employer\u8217\'92s business.\u8221\'94 42 U.S.C. \u167\'A7 2000e(j). Trans World Airlines, Inc. v. Hardison, 432 U.S. 63 (1977) has been the most controlling case over this, which allowed employers to deny accommodations that imposed \u8220\'93more than a de minimis cost.\u8221\'94 Id. at 84. This low threshold favored employers and made the proving of an undue hardship straight-forward. However, with Groff v. DeJoy, 600 U.S. 447 (2023), the Supreme Court clarified from Hardison\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93de minimis\u8221\'94 standard, stating instead that Title VII requires that: \u8220\'93An employer must show that the burden of granting an accommodation would result in substantial increased costs in relation to the conduct of its particular business.\u8221\'94 Id. at 460. This increased standard demands a more in-depth, fact-based inquiry into the actual impact of accommodation, rather than more-than-minor costs. A \u8220\'93reasonable accommodation\u8221\'94 under Title VII is one that effectively resolves the conflict between an employee\u8217\'92s religious practice and workplace requirements, even if it is not the employee\u8217\'92s preferred solution. Ansonia Bd. of Educ. v. Philbrook, 479 U.S. 60, 70 (1986). The employer meets its obligation if the offered accommodation allows the employee to practice their religion without requiring the employer to bear a substantial burden.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 The sections that follow address two issues: first, whether Capital Boost provided reasonable accommodation and whether Barat adequately engaged in that process; additionally, whether Capital Boost can establish undue hardship based on operational disruptions and coworker burdens.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 A.\tab While the Boiler Room Was Likely Inadequate without further modification than offered, Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Failure to Propose Alternatives or Collaborate Meaningfully Undermines His Claim That Capital Boost Violated Title VII. }
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII, a reasonable accommodation is one that allows an employee to meet religious obligations while still fulfilling job requirements, even if it is not the employee\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s preferred option. Ansonia Bd. of Educ. v. Philbrook, 479 U.S. 60, 70 (1986).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 This section considers two questions: whether the boiler room was a reasonable accommodation, and whether Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s refusal to engage in the process weakens his claim.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 1.\tab It Is Likely the Boiler Room Was Not a Reasonable Accommodation Because Its Physical Condition Violated Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Religious Requirements and Proposal for Alterations Likely Did Not Resolve Issues.}
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII, an employer satisfies the duty of accommodation if the employee can practice their religion unless it cannot be done without undue hardship. The accommodation must effectively permit the practice. Ansonia Bd. of Educ. v. Philbrook, 479 U.S. 60, 70 (1986). The Tenth Circuit has emphasized that reasonableness is a fact-specific inquiry, and accommodation is not reasonable if it fails to allow the employee to meet their religious obligations. Tabura v. Kellogg USA, 880 F.3d 544, 550 (2018). Similarly, the court has held that an employer cannot rely on facially available but practically unusable accommodation. Toledo v. Nobel-Sysco, Inc., 892 F.2d 1481, 1489 (1989).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 In Pinsker v. Joint Dist. No. 28J, 735 F.2d 388, 390\endash 91 (1984), the Tenth Circuit upheld an employer\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s leave policy as a reasonable accommodation because it allowed a teacher to observe religious holidays without risking employment, even though it required him to take unpaid leave. The court emphasized that the accommodation was workable in practice and did not force the employee to violate his religious obligations. By contrast, in Tabura, the court found that shift-swapping and vacation time were not necessarily reasonable because they did not consistently allow employees to observe their Sabbath.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Here, Capital Boost offered Barat the boiler room as an alternative prayer space and suggested it could be \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93fixed up.\u8221\'94 While cosmetic improvements might have addressed cleanliness or lighting, The intrinsic factors like the heat from the boiler itself made it unsuitable for prayer. Unlike the unpaid leave in Pinsker, which directly enabled religious observance, the boiler room would not have eliminated the conflict between Barat\u8217\'92s religious obligations and his work environment. Even if altered, the space would still have failed to meet the religious requirement that prayer occur in a clean and dignified setting.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 With this in mind, while Capital Boost\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s offer was seemingly in good faith, it is less likely than not that the boiler room constituted a \u8220\'93reasonable accommodation\u8221\'94 under Title VII, because its inherent characteristics prevented it from allowing Barat to practice his faith as required.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 2.\tab Barat More Likely Than Not Failed to Engage in the Accommodation Process After Rejecting the Boiler Room Without Continuing to Propose any Alternate Solutions or Compromises}
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII, once an employee establishes a prima facie case of religious discrimination, the burden shifts to the employer to show that it either provided a reasonable accommodation or that doing so would cause undue hardship. Toledo v. Nobel-Sysco, Inc., 892 F.2d 1481, 1486 (1989). Courts have emphasized that this duty is reciprocal: while the employer must make good-faith efforts to accommodate, the employee must also cooperate in the process. In Lee v. ABF Freight Sys., Inc., 22 F.3d 1019, 1022\endash 23 (1994), the Tenth Circuit held that an employee undermined his claim by rejecting proposed accommodations without attempting them or offering alternatives. In Brener v. Diagnostic Ctr. Hosp., 671 F.2d 141 (1982), the court explained that an employee must make a good faith attempt to satisfy religious needs through the means offered by the employer.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Here, according to his deposition, Barat rejected the boiler room outright but did not propose any alternative accommodations or engage in further dialogue before his termination. This failure to suggest alternatives weighs against the claim, as courts in the Tenth Circuit have consistently required employees to participate in the process. At the same time, the record shows that the period between his rejection and termination was brief, the short time frame makes it less clear whether his lack of response would be treated as a decisive failure. Accordingly, it is more likely than not that Barat did not adequately engage in the accommodation process, but the timeline reduces the strength of this conclusion.}
