\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 B.\tab Capital Boost Likely Faced an Undue Hardship Due to Operational Disruptions, Even Though the Impact on Coworkers Alone May Not Independently Satisfy the Title VII Threshold. }
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII, an employer need not provide a religious accommodation if doing so would create an \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93undue hardship on the conduct of the employer\u8217\'92s business.\u8221\'94 42 U.S.C. \u167\'A7\u8239\'A02000e(j). In Groff v. DeJoy, 600 U.S. 447, (2023), the Supreme Court clarified that undue hardship requires a showing that the accommodation would impose a substantial burden in the overall context of the employer\u8217\'92s business, not merely a minor inconvenience. Id at 460, 461.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Earlier cases, most notably Trans World Airlines, Inc. v. Hardison, 432 U.S. 63 (1977), had been read to allow denial of accommodations for \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93more than a de minimis cost.\u8221\'94 Id. at 84. While Groff heightened the standard, Hardison and similar cases remain instructive because their factual analyses focused on significant operational burdens such as premium pay, disruption of essential functions, or conflicts with labor agreements. Those examples continue to illustrate the kinds of impacts that can qualify as \u8220\'93substantial\u8221\'94 under the clarified standard.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 This section evaluates whether Capital Boost can establish undue hardship by addressing two questions: whether Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s prayer schedule disrupted sales operations and the company\u8217\'92s return-to-office strategy, and whether coworker resentment and workflow burdens independently or jointly meet the Title VII threshold.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 1.\tab Capital Boost Likely Faced an Undue Hardship Because Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Prayer Schedule Disrupted Core Sales Functions, Undermined Client Engagement, and Threatened the Viability of Its Return-to-Office Strategy. }
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 \tab Under Title VII, an employer may deny religious accommodation if it proves that granting it would impose an undue hardship on the conduct of its business. 42 U.S.C. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e(j). The Supreme Court clarified in Groff v. DeJoy, 600 U.S. 447, 460\endash 61 (2023), that the proper standard requires a showing of a substantial burden in the overall context of the employer\u8217\'92s business. Courts must consider the nature, size, and operating costs of the employer, and coworker impacts are relevant only insofar as they affect the conduct of the business. Id. at 468, 469.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 In EEOC v. JBS USA, LLC, 339 F. Supp. 3d 1135, 1173 (2018), the court found undue hardship where Muslim employees\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92 requests for prayer breaks in a meatpacking plant disrupted production lines and created safety risks. Similarly, in Toledo v. Nobel-Sysco, Inc., 892 F.2d 1481, 1489 (1989), the Tenth Circuit recognized that an accommodation requiring significant operational changes or impairing the employer\u8217\'92s ability to meet business needs could constitute undue hardship. These cases illustrate that when religious accommodation interferes with essential business functions, courts are more likely to find undue hardship.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Here, Capital Boost\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s business model depends heavily on continuous client engagement through phone calls, meetings, and sales quotas. The record shows that Barat\u8217\'92s daily breaks caused missed staff meetings, unanswered client calls, and disruptions to sales operations. Other employees were forced to cover his calls, and management expressed concern that the interruptions undermined the company\u8217\'92s return-to-office strategy, which was viewed as critical to reversing declining sales. Much like the production-line disruptions in JBS USA, Barat\u8217\'92s absences directly impaired the company\u8217\'92s ability to perform its goals. As in Toledo, the accommodation required the employer to absorb significant operational inefficiencies at a time of economic strain.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Because Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s prayer schedule disrupted Capital Boost\u8217\'92s sales operations and threatened its return-to-office initiative, the company can likely demonstrate that continuing the accommodation would have imposed an undue hardship.  Under Title VII, an employer may deny religious accommodation if granting it would impose an undue hardship on the conduct of its business. The Supreme Court has clarified that undue hardship requires a showing that the accommodation would result in a substantial burden in the overall context of the employer\u8217\'92s business, not merely a minor inconvenience. Groff v. DeJoy, 600 U.S. 447, 460\endash 61 (2023).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Courts applying this standard have upheld undue hardship defenses where the economic or operational costs were significant. In Smith v. Pyro Mining Co., 827 F.2d 1081 (1987), the court held that exempting an employee from Sunday work would have required the company to disrupt a continuous\_operation schedule, creating costs substantial enough to constitute undue hardship.  Similarly, in EEOC v. JBS USA, LLC, 339 F. Supp. 3d 1135, 1173 (2018), prayer breaks that halted production lines were deemed an undue hardship. These cases showcase that when accommodation directly impairs essential operations or imposes significant financial burdens, courts are more likely to find undue hardship.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Capital Boost\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s business model depends on uninterrupted client engagement, with nearly all contact being on phone lines. Barat\u8217\'92s prayer breaks left calls unanswered, forced other agents to abandon their own quotas to cover for him. Management also testified that these interruptions undermined the credibility of the company\u8217\'92s return\_to\_office strategy, which was central to its survival in a declining market. Unlike the speculative burdens rejected in some cases, these disruptions were concrete, recurring, and directly impaired Capital Boost\u8217\'92s ability to perform its core revenue\_generating functions. Because Barat\u8217\'92s prayer schedule repeatedly disrupted client engagement and weakened a company\_wide initiative during a period of economic strain, Capital Boost can likely demonstrate that continuing the accommodation would have imposed a substantial burden, and thus an undue hardship, under Title VII.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 2.\tab While Barat\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Prayer Routine Caused Friction Among Coworkers, the Resulting Burden Is Unlikely to Meet the Threshold for Undue Hardship Under Title VII.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Find Cases//}
\par\plain \f1\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Under Title VII, an employer may deny a religious accommodation only if it can show that granting it would impose a substantial burden on the conduct of its business. Groff v. DeJoy, 600 U.S. 447, 460\endash 61 (2023). The Court emphasized that coworker impacts matter only when they translate into actual operational disruption, not when they reflect resentment or dislike.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Courts have given weight to coworker burdens primarily in the context of collective bargaining agreements. In Trans World Airlines, Inc. v. Hardison, 432 U.S. 63 (1977), the Court held that Title VII did not require overriding a collectively bargained seniority system to accommodate Sabbath observance. That reasoning shows that when accommodations conflict with contractual rights or impose premium pay obligations, coworker burdens may amount to undue hardship.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Outside those contexts, courts have been reluctant to credit coworker complaints. In Brown v. Polk County, 61 F.3d 650 (1995), the court rejected coworker hostility as a defense, and in Toledo v. Nobel Sysco, Inc., 892 F.2d 1481 (1989), the Tenth Circuit stressed that inconvenience or dissatisfaction alone is insufficient.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Here, Capital Boost points to coworkers\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92 frustration over covering Barat\u8217\'92s calls and perceptions of preferential treatment. While these concerns reflect tension, they do not relate to collective bargaining rights or premium pay. Absent features, coworker resentment is unlikely to qualify as a substantial burden. Unless Capital Boost can show that resentment materially impaired sales or client retention, this argument is weak under Groff.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0 Accordingly, coworker friction is highly unlikely to support an undue hardship defense in this case.}
